T1  - Financing Investment: The Choice Between Bonds and Bank Loans
AU  - Morellec, Erwan
AU  - Valta, Philip
AU  - Zhdanov, Alexei
Y1  - 2014/12/15
PY  - 2014
DA  - 2015/11/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2014.2005
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2014.2005
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 2580
EP  - 2602
VL  - 61
IS  - 11
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - We build a model of investment and financing decisions to study the choice between bonds and bank loans in a firm?s marginal financing decision and its effects on corporate investment. We show that firms with more growth options, with higher bargaining power in default, operating in more competitive product markets, or facing lower credit supply are more likely to issue bonds. We also demonstrate that, by changing the cost of financing, these characteristics affect the timing of investment. We test these predictions using a sample of U.S. firms and present new evidence that supports our theory. Data, as supplemental material, are available at http://dx.doi.org/10.1287/mnsc.2014.2005. This paper was accepted by Gustavo Manso, finance.
AB  - We build a model of investment and financing decisions to study the choice between bonds and bank loans in a firm?s marginal financing decision and its effects on corporate investment. We show that firms with more growth options, with higher bargaining power in default, operating in more competitive product markets, or facing lower credit supply are more likely to issue bonds. We also demonstrate that, by changing the cost of financing, these characteristics affect the timing of investment. We test these predictions using a sample of U.S. firms and present new evidence that supports our theory. Data, as supplemental material, are available at http://dx.doi.org/10.1287/mnsc.2014.2005. This paper was accepted by Gustavo Manso, finance.
